<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880811-0016 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief: Harris Corp. </HL><SO> </SO><CO> HRS </CO><IN> ERN </IN><TEXT>   Harris Corp. said fourth-quarter net income skidded to $1.8 million, or five cents a share, from $26.2 million, or 63 cents a share, a year earlier, reflecting large charges for operation cutbacks and asset revaluations.    The Melbourne, Fla., information, communications and microelectronics concern said the charges totaled $33.1 million in the year ended June 30. It said &quot;most&quot; of that was charged in the fourth quarter, but declined to elaborate.    It said the charges included a reduction in the carrying value of the company's investment in a foreign joint venture, adjustments to inventories, and costs associated with streamlining operations in its information systems sector.    Revenue slipped 4% to $549 million from $571.6 million.    For the fiscal year, the company reported operating profit of $65.4 million, or $1.63 a share. An extraordinary credit of $35.1 million for a change in accounting methods made net $100.5 million, or $2.50 a share. In fiscal l987, Harris had net income of $84.5 million, or $2.05 a share.    Revenue for the year was about unchanged at $2.1 billion. </TEXT></DOC>